        <div id="EngT" class="hidden">
            
            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 1</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">The Anatomy of Ruby & Output</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Before writing code, understand the machine. A computer CPU only understands binary (0s and 1s). It does not understand English or Ruby. So, how does code work?</p>
                
                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Interpreter vs Compiler (Interview Question)</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2">Ruby is an <strong>Interpreted Language</strong>.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-0 text-base">
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>Compiled (C++, Java):</strong> Code is translated into a machine file (.exe) *before* running. If there is an error, it won't even start.</li>
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>Interpreted (Ruby, Python):</strong> An "Interpreter" reads your code line-by-line and executes it instantly. It's friendlier for learning but slightly slower in raw execution.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">The Art of Output</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">To communicate with the user, we send data to "STDOUT" (Standard Output), which is your screen.</p>
                
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6">
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>puts</code>: Adds a "newline" character (<code>\n</code>) at the end. Think of it as hitting "Enter" after writing.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>print</code>: Writes text but keeps the cursor at the end of the line.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>p</code>: The debugger's friend. It prints the *raw* value (e.g., it shows quotes around strings).</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Hello"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">print</span> <span class="str">"World"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">print</span> <span class="str">"!"</span><br>
                    <span class="com"># Output:<br>
                    # Hello<br>
                    # World!</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 2</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Variables, Objects & Symbols</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">In Ruby, <strong>Everything is an Object</strong>. Even a simple number like <code>5</code> is an object with methods attached to it.</p>
                
                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">1. The Standard Data Types</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6">
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>String:</strong> Text data. <code>"Hello"</code>.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>Integer:</strong> Whole numbers. <code>100</code>.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>Float:</strong> Decimals. <code>10.5</code>.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>Boolean:</strong> Logic gates. <code>true</code> / <code>false</code>.</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Pro Concept: Symbols (:name)</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2">You will see this everywhere in Ruby (e.g., <code>:status</code>, <code>:id</code>). A <strong>Symbol</strong> is like a lightweight String.</p>
                    <br>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2"><strong>Why use them?</strong></p>
                    <p class="text-base mb-0">Every time you type <code>"hello"</code>, Ruby creates a *new* object in memory. But <code>:hello</code> is created only **once**. It saves massive amounts of memory in large applications.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">name</span> = <span class="str">"Alice"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">status</span> = <span class="sym">:active</span>  <span class="com"># This is a Symbol</span><br><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> name.class   <span class="com"># Output: String</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> status.class <span class="com"># Output: Symbol</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 3</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">String Engineering</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">String manipulation is 50% of programming (parsing logs, user data, text processing).</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">Interpolation (The Gold Standard)</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Never use <code>+</code> to join strings with variables. It is slow and error-prone. Use <code>#{}</code> inside double quotes.</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">Mutable vs Immutable</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">In Ruby, strings are <strong>mutable</strong>. You can change them in place.</p>
                
                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">greeting</span> = <span class="str">"hello"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">greeting</span> &lt;&lt; <span class="str">" world"</span>  <span class="com"># Appends to the same memory location</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> greeting  <span class="com"># "hello world"</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="var">text</span> = <span class="str">"ruby is fun"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> text.upcase    <span class="com"># "RUBY IS FUN" (Returns a COPY)</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> text.upcase!   <span class="com"># "RUBY IS FUN" (Changes ORIGINAL variable)</span>
                </div>
                
                <div class="warning-box bg-red-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#ff7b72] p-5 my-5 rounded-r-lg text-[#ff7b72]">
                    <strong class="text-lg block mb-1">Bang Methods (!):</strong> Be careful with methods ending in <code>!</code>. They modify the original data permanently.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 4</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Input & Type Conversion</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">When you get input from a user or a file, it is <strong>always a String</strong>. Even if the user types "50", the computer sees "50" (text), not 50 (number).</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">The Chomp & Convert Combo</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6">
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>gets</code>: Reads input + Enter key (newline).</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>chomp</code>: Removes the Enter key.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>to_i</code> / <code>to_f</code>: Converts text to Integer or Float.</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Enter your age:"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">age_text</span> = <span class="kwd">gets</span>.chomp  <span class="com"># User types "25" -> "25"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">age_num</span> = age_text.to_i  <span class="com"># "25" -> 25</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Next year you will be #{age_num + 1}"</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 5</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Control Flow & Logic</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Beyond standard <code>if/else</code>, Ruby offers elegant ways to handle logic. 

[Image of programming control flow diagram]
</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">1. The 'Unless' Keyword</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">It means "If NOT". It runs the code only if the condition is **false**. It reads like natural English.</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">2. Ternary Operator (One-Liner)</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Great for assigning values based on a quick check.</p>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">battery</span> = <span class="num">10</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Standard If</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">if</span> battery < <span class="num">20</span><br>
                      <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Low Battery"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span><br><br>

                    <span class="com"># Unless (Ruby Special)</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">unless</span> battery == <span class="num">100</span><br>
                      <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Not fully charged"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Ternary: condition ? true_val : false_val</span><br>
                    <span class="var">status</span> = battery > <span class="num">50</span> ? <span class="str">"Good"</span> : <span class="str">"Bad"</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 6</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Arrays & Iterators (DSA Core)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Arrays in Ruby are dynamic. You don't need to define the size. They grow as you add data.</p>
                
                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Stack Operations (DSA)</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2">Arrays naturally act as a "Stack" data structure (Last In, First Out).</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-0 text-base">
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>push:</strong> Add to top.</li>
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>pop:</strong> Remove from top.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">The Power of .map (Transformation)</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg"><code>.each</code> is for *doing* something. <code>.map</code> is for *transforming* data. It returns a new array.</p>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">nums</span> = [<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">3</span>]<br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># .map creates a NEW array where every item is squared</span><br>
                    <span class="var">squared</span> = nums.map { |n| n * n }<br><br>
                    
                    <span class="kwd">p</span> squared  <span class="com"># Output: [1, 4, 9]</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">p</span> nums     <span class="com"># Output: [1, 2, 3] (Original is safe)</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 7</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Hashes (Key-Value Pairs)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Known as "Dictionaries" or "HashMaps" in other languages. This is the **fastest** way to find data. While an Array requires scanning 0, 1, 2... a Hash jumps directly to the key.</p>
                
                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="com"># New Syntax (JSON style)</span><br>
                    <span class="var">person</span> = { <span class="sym">name:</span> <span class="str">"John"</span>, <span class="sym">age:</span> <span class="num">30</span>, <span class="sym">city:</span> <span class="str">"NYC"</span> }<br><br>
                    
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> person[<span class="sym">:name</span>]  <span class="com"># Output: John</span><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Adding data</span><br>
                    person[<span class="sym">:job</span>] = <span class="str">"Dev"</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Iterating a Hash</span><br>
                    person.each <span class="kwd">do</span> |key, value|<br>
                      <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"#{key} is #{value}"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 8</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Methods (Functions)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">To write clean code, we follow <strong>DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)</strong>. We bundle logic into methods.</p>
                
                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Implicit Return</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-0">In Ruby, you don't need to type <code>return</code>. The method automatically returns the result of the **last line** of code.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="kwd">def</span> <span class="met">add_numbers</span>(<span class="var">a</span>, <span class="var">b</span>)<br>
                      <span class="var">sum</span> = a + b<br>
                      sum  <span class="com"># This is automatically returned</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="var">result</span> = add_numbers(<span class="num">5</span>, <span class="num">10</span>)<br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> result  <span class="com"># 15</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="HinT">
            
            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>

                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 1</span>
                
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Ruby ki Anatomy aur Output</h2>
                
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Code likhne se pehle machine ko samajhna zaruri hai. CPU sirf binary (0s aur 1s) samajhta hai. Wo English ya Ruby nahi jaanta. Toh, code kaam kaise karta hai?</p>
                
                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Interpreter vs Compiler (Interview Question)</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2">Ruby ek <strong>Interpreted Language</strong> hai.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-0 text-base">
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>Compiled (C++, Java):</strong> Pura code pehle ek machine file (.exe) mein convert hota hai, fir chalta hai. Agar ek bhi galti hui, to program start hi nahi hoga.</li>
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>Interpreted (Ruby, Python):</strong> Yahan ek "Interpreter" hota hai jo aapka code line-by-line padhta hai aur run karta hai. Ye seekhne mein aasaan hai par thoda slow ho sakta hai heavy tasks ke liye.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">Output dikhane ki Kala</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">User se baat karne ke liye hum "STDOUT" (Screen) par data bhejte hain.</p>
                
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6">
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>puts</code>: Ye text print karta hai aur end mein "Enter" daba deta hai (Cursor nayi line par chala jata hai).</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>print</code>: Ye text print karta hai par cursor wahin chipka rehta hai.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>p</code>: Ye debugging ke liye hai. Ye raw data dikhata hai (Jaise strings ke aas paas quotes bhi dikhayega).</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Hello"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">print</span> <span class="str">"World"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">print</span> <span class="str">"!"</span><br>
                    <span class="com"># Output:<br>
                    # Hello<br>
                    # World!</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 2</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Variables, Objects aur Symbols</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Ruby mein <strong>Har cheez ek Object hai</strong>. Even ek simple number <code>5</code> bhi ek object hai jiske paas methods hote hain.</p>
                
                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">1. Standard Data Types</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6">
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>String:</strong> Text data. <code>"Mera Naam"</code>.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>Integer:</strong> Poore number. <code>100</code>.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>Float:</strong> Point wale number. <code>10.5</code>.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><strong>Boolean:</strong> Haan ya Na. <code>true</code> / <code>false</code>.</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Pro Concept: Symbols (:name)</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2">Aap Ruby code mein har jagah colon wale words dekhenge (jaise <code>:status</code>, <code>:id</code>). Inhe <strong>Symbol</strong> kehte hain.</p>
                    <br>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2"><strong>Inka use kyu karein?</strong></p>
                    <p class="text-base mb-0">Jab aap <code>"hello"</code> likhte hain, Ruby har baar memory mein ek nayi jagah banata hai. Par <code>:hello</code> (symbol) pure program mein sirf **ek baar** banta hai. Ye badi applications mein memory bachata hai.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">name</span> = <span class="str">"Alice"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">status</span> = <span class="sym">:active</span>  <span class="com"># Ye Symbol hai</span><br><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> name.class   <span class="com"># Output: String</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> status.class <span class="com"># Output: Symbol</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 3</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">String Engineering (Text ka Khel)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Programming ka 50% hissa sirf text handle karna hota hai (Logs padhna, user data saf karna).</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">Interpolation (Sahi Tarika)</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Variables ko string ke saath jodne ke liye kabhi <code>+</code> mat use karo. Ye slow hai. Hamesha <code>#{}</code> use karo double quotes ke andar.</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">Mutable vs Immutable</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Ruby mein Strings <strong>mutable</strong> hoti hain. Matlab aap unhe original jagah par hi badal sakte hain.</p>
                
                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">greeting</span> = <span class="str">"hello"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">greeting</span> &lt;&lt; <span class="str">" world"</span>  <span class="com"># Ye usi variable mein jud gaya</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> greeting  <span class="com"># "hello world"</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="var">text</span> = <span class="str">"ruby is fun"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> text.upcase    <span class="com"># "RUBY IS FUN" (Ye ek COPY return karta hai)</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> text.upcase!   <span class="com"># "RUBY IS FUN" (Ye ORIGINAL variable badal deta hai)</span>
                </div>
                
                <div class="warning-box bg-red-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#ff7b72] p-5 my-5 rounded-r-lg text-[#ff7b72]">
                    <strong class="text-lg block mb-1">Bang Methods (!):</strong> Jin methods ke end mein <code>!</code> hota hai, unse savdhaan rahein. Wo original data ko permanent change kar dete hain.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 4</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Input & Type Conversion</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Jab aap user se input lete hain, wo <strong>hamesha String</strong> hota hai. Agar user "50" likhta hai, computer use text maanta hai, number nahi.</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">Chomp aur Convert ka Formula</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6">
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>gets</code>: Input leta hai + Enter key (newline) bhi save karta hai.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>chomp</code>: Enter key (new line) ko kaat deta hai.</li>
                    <li class="mb-3 text-lg"><code>to_i</code> / <code>to_f</code>: Text ko Integer ya Float mein convert karta hai.</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Apni age batayein:"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">age_text</span> = <span class="kwd">gets</span>.chomp  <span class="com"># User ne likha "25" -> Variable bana "25"</span><br>
                    <span class="var">age_num</span> = age_text.to_i  <span class="com"># "25" -> ban gaya 25 (Maths ke layak)</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Agle saal aap #{age_num + 1} ke honge"</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 5</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Control Flow (Faisla Lena)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Standard <code>if/else</code> ke alawa, Ruby mein logic likhne ke kaafi sundar tarike hain. </p>
                
                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">1. The 'Unless' Keyword (Ruby Special)</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Iska matlab hai "Agar NAHI". Ye code tabhi chalta hai jab condition **Jhoot (False)** ho.</p>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">2. Ternary Operator (Ek Line ka Magic)</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Chhoti conditions ke liye 5 line ka code likhne ki zarurat nahi hai.</p>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">battery</span> = <span class="num">10</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Aam Zindagi (Standard If)</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">if</span> battery < <span class="num">20</span><br>
                      <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Low Battery"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span><br><br>

                    <span class="com"># Mentos Zindagi (Unless)</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">unless</span> battery == <span class="num">100</span><br>
                      <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"Full charge nahi hai"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Ternary: condition ? agar_sach_hai : agar_jhoot_hai</span><br>
                    <span class="var">status</span> = battery > <span class="num">50</span> ? <span class="str">"Badhiya"</span> : <span class="str">"Khatra"</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 6</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Arrays & Iterators (DSA ki Jaan)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Ruby mein Arrays dynamic hote hain. Size batane ki zarurat nahi, jitna data daaloge wo badhte jayenge.</p>
                
                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Stack Operations (DSA)</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-2">Arrays naturally "Stack" ki tarah kaam karte hain (Last In, First Out).</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-0 text-base">
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>push:</strong> Upar add karo.</li>
                        <li class="mb-2"><strong>pop:</strong> Upar se hatao.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-[#d2a8ff] mt-8 text-2xl mb-4">.map ki Taakat (Transformation)</h3>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg"><code>.each</code> sirf loop ghumane ke liye hai. <code>.map</code> data ko **badalne (transform)** ke liye hai. Ye ek naya array return karta hai.</p>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="var">nums</span> = [<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">3</span>]<br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># .map ek NAYA array banata hai jisme har number square ho gaya</span><br>
                    <span class="var">squared</span> = nums.map { |n| n * n }<br><br>
                    
                    <span class="kwd">p</span> squared  <span class="com"># Output: [1, 4, 9]</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">p</span> nums     <span class="com"># Output: [1, 2, 3] (Purana wala safe hai)</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 7</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Hashes (Key-Value Pairs)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Ise dusri languages mein "Dictionaries" ya "HashMap" kehte hain. Data dhoondne ka ye **sabse tez** tarika hai. Array mein computer ko 0, 1, 2... karke dhoondna padta hai, Hash mein wo seedha "Key" par jump karta hai.</p>
                
                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="com"># Naya Syntax (JSON style)</span><br>
                    <span class="var">person</span> = { <span class="sym">name:</span> <span class="str">"Amit"</span>, <span class="sym">age:</span> <span class="num">30</span>, <span class="sym">city:</span> <span class="str">"Delhi"</span> }<br><br>
                    
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> person[<span class="sym">:name</span>]  <span class="com"># Output: Amit</span><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Data add karna</span><br>
                    person[<span class="sym">:job</span>] = <span class="str">"Coder"</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="com"># Hash par loop chalana</span><br>
                    person.each <span class="kwd">do</span> |key, value|<br>
                      <span class="kwd">puts</span> <span class="str">"#{key} hai #{value}"</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="chapter-card bg-[#161b22] border border-[#30363d] rounded-xl p-10 mb-12 relative overflow-hidden">
                <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-1 bg-[#58a6ff] h-full"></div>
                <span class="chapter-number inline-block text-[#58a6ff] font-bold uppercase tracking-wider mb-1 text-sm">Chapter 8</span>
                <h2 class="text-white text-3xl border-b-2 border-[#30363d] pb-4 mt-0">Methods (Functions)</h2>
                <p class="mb-5 text-lg">Saaf code likhne ke liye hum <strong>DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)</strong> rule follow karte hain. Hum logic ko methods mein band kar dete hain taaki baar baar na likhna pade.</p>
                
                <div class="concept-box bg-blue-500/10 border-l-4 border-[#1f6feb] p-6 my-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <span class="concept-title font-bold text-[#79c0ff] block mb-2 text-lg uppercase">Implicit Return (Ruby ka Magic)</span>
                    <p class="text-base mb-0">Ruby mein <code>return</code> likhna zaruri nahi hota. Method ki **aakhiri line** ka jo bhi result hoga, wo automatically return ho jata hai.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="code-box bg-[#0d1117] border border-[#30363d] rounded-lg p-6 font-mono text-lg overflow-x-auto my-6 text-[#e6edf3] border-l-6 border-accent-green shadow-inner shadow-black/20">
                    <span class="kwd">def</span> <span class="met">jod_do</span>(<span class="var">a</span>, <span class="var">b</span>)<br>
                      <span class="var">sum</span> = a + b<br>
                      sum  <span class="com"># Ye khud wapas chala jayega (return)</span><br>
                    <span class="kwd">end</span><br><br>
                    
                    <span class="var">result</span> = jod_do(<span class="num">5</span>, <span class="num">10</span>)<br>
                    <span class="kwd">puts</span> result  <span class="com"># 15</span>
                </div>




        </div>

    </div>

    <script>
        const englishBtn = document.getElementById("englishBtn");
        const hinglishBtn = document.getElementById("hinglishBtn");
        const EngT = document.getElementById("EngT");
        const HinT = document.getElementById("HinT");

        // Function to set active button state using Tailwind classes
        function setActiveButton(button) {
            // Remove active classes from both
            englishBtn.classList.remove('bg-[#238636]', 'text-white', 'shadow-md', 'shadow-green-700/40');
            englishBtn.classList.add('text-[#8b949e]');
            
            hinglishBtn.classList.remove('bg-[#238636]', 'text-white', 'shadow-md', 'shadow-green-700/40');
            hinglishBtn.classList.add('text-[#8b949e]');

            // Add active classes to the selected button
            button.classList.add('bg-[#238636]', 'text-white', 'shadow-md', 'shadow-green-700/40');
            button.classList.remove('text-[#8b949e]');
        }

        englishBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            EngT.classList.remove('hidden');
            HinT.classList.add('hidden');
            setActiveButton(englishBtn);
        });

        hinglishBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            HinT.classList.remove('hidden');
            EngT.classList.add('hidden');
            setActiveButton(hinglishBtn);
        });

        // Initial setup on load (default to Hinglish if active class is present)
        if (hinglishBtn.classList.contains('active')) {
            hinglishBtn.click();
        } else {
            englishBtn.click();
        }






